cd
Once you have a folder, you can move into it using the cd command. cd means change directory. You invoke it specifying a folder to move into. You can specify a folder name, or an entire path.

Example:

Bash
mkdir fruits
cd fruits
Now you are into the fruits folder.

You can use the .. special path to indicate the parent folder:

Bash
cd .. #back to the home folder
Important cd Shortcuts to Know
Navigating the filesystem becomes much faster once you know these special path shortcuts:

cd (or cd ~): Takes you instantly back to your user's Home directory (e.g., /home/username or /Users/username), no matter where you currently are.

cd -: Takes you back to the previous directory you were working in. It acts like a "back" button on a web browser, letting you toggle easily between two distant folders.

cd /: Takes you all the way to the Root directory—the topmost folder of the entire system hierarchy.